  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Set Matrix Zeroes\n\nIf a matrix cell is zero, set its entire row and column to zero in place.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: matrix = [[1,1,1],[1,0,1],[1,1,1]]\nOutput: [[1,0,1],[0,0,0],[1,0,1]]\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: matrix = [[0,1,2],[3,4,5]]\nOutput: [[0,0,0],[0,4,5]]\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: matrix = [[1]]\nOutput: [[1]]\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Inputs are sized for local offline execution.\n- Return the value described by the method signature.",
  "editorial": "Use direct arithmetic, matrix indexing, or bit operations to preserve the required invariants while keeping extra state small.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def setZeroes(self, matrix):\n        rows = {r for r, row in enumerate(matrix) for c, value in enumerate(row) if value == 0}\n        cols = {c for r, row in enumerate(matrix) for c, value in enumerate(row) if value == 0}\n        for r in range(len(matrix)):\n            for c in range(len(matrix[0])):\n                if r in rows or c in cols: matrix[r][c] = 0\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Watch fixed-width integer boundaries where the prompt requires them.",
    "For matrix mutation, mark or capture affected rows and columns before overwriting."
  ],
